a lot farther ahead. Well, the same thing can be

17:48.701 --> 17:53.368
said, I'm pretty sure, of all coastal states. to 
varying degrees. You pass a law to appease some

17:56.534 --> 18:00.501
group and then you forget it. You don't try to 
enforce it. So that would be a start. The other

18:04.007 --> 18:19.913
thing, at a higher level, I think the EPA is finally 
recognizing that you can't develop

18:04.007 --> 18:19.913
environmental constraints on estuaries as a 
whole. You've got to accept the fact that

18:20.399 --> 18:27.688
estuaries in Alaska are different from estuaries 
in Florida. And it's going to take a further

18:28.369 --> 18:47.352
subdivision of U.S. regional problems and then 
specific ordinances, laws, call them what you

18:28.369 --> 18:47.352
will, measures to deal with those problems in 
specific areas and not try to blanket Alaska and

18:28.369 --> 18:47.352
Florida. But none of this will come about if the 
public doesn't demand it, and if they don't

18:48.901 --> 19:05.550
realize that when scientists talk about the 
concern for the small fiddler crabs, they're not

18:48.901 --> 19:05.550
